Delta State Government has explained the rationale behind the upward review of the 2020 budget from the previously revised N279, 784 billion as already passed into law by the state government to N282, 331billion. The Commissioner for Information, Mr. Charles Aniagwu who briefed journalists yesterday said the 2020 budget which was initially passed into law in December, 2019, was reviewed downward in May this year 2020 following the outbreak of the ravaging Covid-19 Pandemic disease with its attendant economic crisis. He added that the upward review of the budget within two months of the downward review was necessitated by the Federal Government’s plan for development and implementing a nationally responsive intergrated policy frame work aimed at addressing the fiscal and economic distortions caused by the Covid-19 Pandemic. According to him, ”On this note, the Federal Government advised state governments to carry out a review of their budgets, the review is expected to be designed along guidelines sent to the states from the Federal Government, designed in Collaboration with World Bank. In compliance with the above advise, states will be able to access stimulus supports such as grants and palliatives from the Federal Government and other multilateral organizations, particularly the World Bank and the reviewed budget is to reflect Covid-19 responsive programmes and projects implementation expenditure. While in consideration of the forgoing therefore, it has become imperative to present a revised 2020 budget that realigns and targets expenditure towards projects with potentials of reflecting the economy from downturn, alleviating the plight of poor households, the vulnerable, provide food security and give Supports to small and medium scale Enterprises that are highly impacted by the Covid-19 Pandemic.”